  "why": "The paper goes beyond merely reporting failures: it links crash-triggering inputs to the model internals by showing that crash-triggering state sequences induce distinct neuron activation patterns (t-SNE visualization, clustering) and by building an abnormal-behavior detector based on those internal activation patterns. It also demonstrates that using these findings to fine-tune a model (DNN-based ACAS Xu) substantially reduces crashes without harming normal performance. However, the paper does not provide deeper diagnostic explanations of WHY the model fails in terms of specific underlying vulnerabilities such as reliance on spurious features, dataset bias, or overfitting; the analysis stays at the level of statistical/internal-pattern correlation rather than causal attribution to particular model weaknesses. This matches the definition of Medium: partial diagnostic insight via model internals/statistical failure patterns, but not explanations linking failures to underlying vulnerabilities.",
  "evidence": "Abstract (p.378): \"We show inspiring findings that crash-triggering states, though they look normal, induce distinct neuron activation patterns compared with normal states. We further develop an abnormal behavior detector to harden all the evaluated models and repair them with the findings of MDPFuzz to significantly enhance their robustness without sacrificing accuracy.\"\n\nRoot Cause Analysis / Sec. 7.3 (p.387): \"The neuron activations of crash-triggering state sequences found by MDPFuzz have a clear boundary with normal and randomly mutated sequences, which shows that the crash-triggering states can trigger the models’ abnormal internal logics. The results are promisingly consistent across all models of different paradigms.\" \n\nEnhancement / Sec. 7.4 (p.387): \"We report the performance of our detector on test data. The area under the receiver operating characteristic curve (AUC-ROC) is above 0.78 for each model, indicating that our detector can simultaneously achieve good precision and recall in detecting abnormal model logics.\" \n\nRepair results / Sec. 7.4 (p.387): \"we present the results of comparing the models in DNN-based ACAS Xu before and after repairing, which show that the #crash detected by MDPFuzz in 12 hours after model repairing is substantially lower, at 29, than 139 before repairing... on the 3,000 randomly-selected normal sequences... the average cumulative rewards of the models before and after repair are close, which are 30.73 and 30.74, respectively.\" \n\nDesign / Sec. 5.1 and Alg.2 (p.382–383): Sensitivity estimation is used to prioritize seeds (internal-behavior-based metric): Alg.2 returns \"|r - rΔ| / ||ΔS||2\" as an estimate of local sensitivity, showing use of internal-behavior/statistical measures for guidance.\n\nNote: While these quotations show the paper links failures to internal activation patterns and uses statistical/internal metrics to diagnose and mitigate failures, the paper does not offer causal attributions such as \"model relies on spurious feature X\" or \"dataset bias Y causes failures,\" which is why the assigned value is Medium rather than High."
